"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:4.8.3.1\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">4.8.3.1</span> Embalming oils</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">ἀλόη</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(aloē)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John19:39\">JHN 19:39</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">ἄρωμα</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(arōma)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark16:1\">MRK 16:1</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke23:56\">LUK 23:56</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke24:1\">LUK 24:1</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John19:40\">JHN 19:40</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">μύρον</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(muron)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke23:56\">LUK 23:56</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">σμύρνα</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(smurna)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John19:39\">JHN 19:39</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>Embalming oils were aromatic oils or salves used especially in preparing a dead body for burial in a way that it would be preserved. See also <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">10.6.1.1 Myrrh&lt;REALIA:10.6.1.1&gt;</a>.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr16:14\">2CH 16:14</a> we find the Hebrew expression <em>bsamim uznim mruqachim</em> in the context of the burial of King Asa of Judah. The text says that spices and aromatic oils were placed in the tomb (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Contemporary English Version\">CEV</abbr> “the tomb was filled with spices and sweet-smelling oils”). There is no reason to assume that Asa’s body was embalmed (like Jacob’s body in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen50:2\">GEN 50:2</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen50:3\">GEN 50:3</a>), although <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> comes close with “They used spices and perfumed oils to prepare his body for burial.”</p>\n<p>In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke23:56\">LUK 23:56</a> translators may use a descriptive phrase to render the Greek word <em>muron</em>, for example, “perfumed oil for preserving the body” or “… to keep the body from rotting.”</p>\n<p>Ingredients mentioned in the New Testament for embalming oils are “myrrh” (<em>smurna</em> in Greek) and “aloes” (<em>aloē</em> in Greek). Most translators borrow terms for these ingredients and then use some kind of marginal note to explain the nature of their substance.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
